\begin_layout Standard
Although individuals in IDP camps share tents with other co-occupants, whom
 they may be more likely to infect than occupants of different tents, we
 ignore spatial structure in our model and assume a well-mixed population.
 This is justified because individuals from different tents share common
 spaces (e.g.
 letrines) and have frequent interactions with each other, especially among
 children.
 Consequently, our following derivation of the transmissivity parameter
 itself, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, is not spatially explicit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rate at which susceptible individuals become exposed is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda_{i}=\sum_{j=1}^{n}\tau C_{ij}\frac{\beta_{\PP}P_{j}+\beta_{\A}A_{j}+\beta_{\I}I_{j}+\beta_{\HH}H_{j}}{N_{j}},\label{eq:lambda}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is the average number of contacts that individuals of class 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 have with individuals of class 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 per day and 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the total population size of class 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 We parameterized 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{ij}$
\end_inset

 by multiplying the mean number of total contacts that individuals from
 a population class 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 have per day, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}$
\end_inset

, by the probability of random interaction with individuals of class 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 Considering a well-mixed population, this probability is proportional to
 class 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

's fraction of the total population, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{ij}=c_{i}N_{j}/N$
\end_inset

.
 If interventions are absent, we consider demographic-classes only and,
