\begin_layout Subsection*
Epidemiological severity assumptions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In NWS, there are 4 active and 2 planed COVID-19 referral hospitals, with
 a current capacity of 66 ventilators, 74 ICU beds and 355 ward beds for
 4.2 million people 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "REACH_syriaOverview,UNOCHA_CCTC_numbers"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Estimations based on an exponential growth model from Hariri et al.
 predicted a collapse of health facilities 8 weeks into an outbreak 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "hariri_SyriaForecast_2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Although we do not have access to official data on healthcare occupancy,
 the currently reported number of cases suggests that this scenario could
 already have been reached 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "UNOCHA_collapse"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Hence, we considered a worst-case scenario in which individuals will not
 have access to healthcare and assumed that all critical cases (those requiring
 ICU care) would die.
 However, there is greater uncertainty about the fate of severe cases, those
 requiring hospitalization but not ICU care.
 We therefore considered a compartment for severe cases to account for a
 longer infectious period if they stay in the camp (see compartment 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{i}$
\end_inset

, Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Diagram"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 This compartment also helped us model some interventions more realistically,
 for example by noting that the symptoms of severe cases are incompatible
 with self-isolation.
 To estimate upper and lower bounds for the outcome variables of our model,
 we simulated two possible scenarios for the fate of this compartment: one
 in which all cases recover, and another in which all die.
 In the simulations presented in the Main Text, we consider the worst-case
 scenario in which all of these cases die.
\end_layout

