Interventions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The interventions we consider are modelled by modifying the rate at which
 individuals become exposed (the term 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

, Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lambda"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), adding new population classes that govern behavioural changes (behaviour-clas
ses), and/or adding a compartment to consider the time until detection of
 symptoms (see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "BROKEN: Ref: fig:DiagramOnset"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

 can be factorized in four terms, the interventions may influence one or
 several of these terms.
 The factors present in 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

 and the terms modulating them in the interventions are (see Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lambdaInterv"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

): i) the maximum transmissibility, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, which is reduced in some interventions by a factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{ij}$
\end_inset

, when interactions are restricted to buffer zones (see below for details);
 ii) the average number of contacts that individuals in class 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 have per day, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 This quantity can either be uniformly reduced across all classes, or the
 contact rate of class 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 with class 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 can be modified.
 We model this modification of contact rates using the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{ij}$
\end_inset

; iii) the probability of encounter between members of class 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 in a well-mixed population, 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{j}/N$
\end_inset

.
 This probability can vary by modifying the visibility of a member of class
 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 to a member of class 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 , which we express with the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{ij}$
\end_inset

; and iv) the probablility of becoming infected by individuals at specific
 stages of the disease (e.g.
 for hospitalized individuals this is encoded in the term 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{\HH}H_{j}/N_{j}$
\end_inset

) can also be modified by specific factors.
 Only the terms for individuals at the clinical symptomatic (
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

) and hospitalized (
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

) stages are modified in our interventions, through the parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{\I}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{\HH}$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 Following these considerations, the generic form of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

 under the interventions becomes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
